Anyway, #PEACEMAKER was fantastic from start to finish. Fully loved every minute and every moment.

Now if you'll excuse me, I'm off to learn a Wig Wam dance routine.

Peacemaker and Adebayo being the last ones standing to fight was perfect because they were the tools of their parents and they escaped them - and also kept the world from becoming tools of the butterflies as well.

But Chris knows that to help the butterflies, he and his friends would have to give up their lives, their minds, and become tools for what someone else considers the greatest good. And he just can't go back to that. He just escaped that life. How can he just submit again?

By killing his father, Peacemaker chose to no longer act as anyone's tool and instead do what he thought was the right thing to do.

When Goff explained the butterflies' purpose on Earth, it SOUNDS noble. It sounds like something good. Saving the world.

Peacemaker lived his entire life with his father in his head. His father used him a tool to his bidding, what he thought was "right" even though Auggie was an actual piece of human garbage. Amanda Waller exploited this brainwashing and used him as a tool as well.

But when PM ended up killing the cow and and by extension, the butterflies, I was... upset? You doomed us, Peacemaker. 

But the thing that Peacemaker does so well, and this is all James Gunn, is interweaving Peacemaker's assumedly disparate plotlines together perfectly.

When the credits rolled, I was... quiet. I had to take a moment. When I found out what the butterflies wanted, my immediate reaction was that it was a good thing. They were here to save us from ourselves. I was rooting for them, for Chris to see their side and save the world.

RT @AmberofSolo: I think a conversation needs to be had about how large chunks of fandom no longer know how to interact with a piece of med…

TBS, theorizing about future media is great! But I think in general, we need to stop letting our theories and expectations about how a story sets up the next story affect how we feel about said story. Take in the self-contained story and judge the media on itself. /end

Sites like ScreenCrush, New Rockstars, ScreenRant and FilmTheory to a lesser extent, among others, pay their bills with clickbaity headlines about how a current story is existing in service of a future story. I don't blame them, but it contributes to the problem.

But for all its flaws, Book of Boba Fett was (and should have been) primarily focused on Boba and his story. Wanting to see Qi'ra or Han and Baby Ben or some other character is fair but whole theories were hinged on cameo appearances instead of the story being told.

I get it though. Mando Season 2 was a series of vaguely interconnected backdoor pilots with some storyline. I can only assume people expected that BOBF would be the same - and really, the two episodes that focused on Mando and Luke instead? Absolutely connective tissue.

The Book of Boba Fett finale dropped a few hours and I already see people upset that their theories about setting up future projects through the use of cameos didn't come true, or their easter eggs to other characters didn't happen.

No Way Home was about doing the right thing no matter what you'll lose. But a lot of theories were far more concerned with connecting to Multiverse of Madness and even moreso, connecting to the Sony universe. Processing Peter's story and arc was secondary to all that.

Wandavision was an absolutely beautiful tale of grief and loss but because we knew Multiverse of Madness was coming, a lot of theories ignored the story that was being told in favor of trying to predict how the NEXT story would be told.

Wandavision, Loki, No Way Home, even Venom and the upcoming Morbius are subjects of theory fodder, not about the movies themselves, but what could happen in those movies to serve the greater overarching universal storyline.

People build entire theories on what will happen in a piece of media based on upcoming projects rather than just looking at the story being told.

We saw this a lot with the MCU last year. So many theories were centered around HOW we were gonna get to Multiverse of Madness.

I think a conversation needs to be had about how large chunks of fandom no longer know how to interact with a piece of media anymore.

In this era of connected universe storytelling, people are more concerned with if/how something is going to tease the NEXT project.

Not proud of this one at all

But this has been my geology/chemistry-based theory about Skeleton Lake. Thanks for reading, and thanks for changing the release date of the podcast so I can listen at work instead of on my days off. Y'all are great @RedWebPod @_TrevorC @AlfredoPlays

I will admit that I did some research before posting this and I could not find data on the chemical composition of Skeleton Lake's water so I have no idea if there are sulfuric remnants there or not, nor do i know if there is sulfuric anything in them bones.
People stay tf away from the lake and it loses it's sulfuric composition again. Tadaaaaa skeleton lake.

Fast forward to the 1800s. Another geothermal vent has opened and the lake is developing sulfuric composition again. A tourist group from Greece and their Southeast Asian guide come to the lake, go for a swim, and go melty melty. Tada, 14 1800s Cretans and 1 1800s SE Asian.

The earth shifts, the geothermal vent shifts elsewhere and over time, with precipitation and freezing yada yada, the lake loses the high acidic composition and becomes just a lake again. Everyone forgets the lake ate people.

Potentially these processionals or whatever that came by here could lead to a large number of bodies at one time? Drinking the water would have a pretty terrible effect as well. Huge body count. Explains why it was talked about in 900 C.E.

So my theory is that the lake became a hot spring that people visited but at some point around 700 C.E., the geothermal vents turning it into a hot spring acid-sulfated the water to the point that it was actively burning people to death.
ANYWAY. All of this to say is that the shifting of rocks and the like can cause geothermal springs, especially in orogeny zones, to come and go. Maybe even separated by a thousand years.

A tour guide in New Zealand told me how a guy went off the path in a hot springs location and his foot went through acid-sulfate mud. By the time he pulled his foot out and peeled his sock off, his foot was practically gone. Bad stuff.

Something that can occasionally happen with geothermal springs is that they can become acid-sulfate springs. That is to say - they have a high sulfuric acid content. These things can be nasty sons of bees.

This orogeny and friction causes geothermal activity. The Himalayas don't get VOLCANOS because both plates are thrusting upwards instead of one being subducted into the mantle and melting, but there is still geothermal activity. There are numerous hot springs in the Himalayas.

Skeleton Lake is in the Himalayas. The Himalayas are an ongoing orogeny - which is fancy geology words meaning an area of mountain building caused by two tectonic plates - in this case the Indian and Eurasian plates - shoving up against each other.
